 closing it entirely through service reductions, entirely through new taxes and fees, or any mix in between.</p>

    <div class="calc-shell">
      <div class="gap-banner">
        <div class="gv">$283.2M</div>
        <div class="gl">THE YEARLY REVENUE GAP THAT MUST BE CLOSED</div>
      </div>

      <div class="slider-zone">
        <div class="slider-ends">
          <span class="left">&#9664; Cut Services</span>
          <span class="mid">Drag to choose how the gap is closed</span>
          <span class="right">Raise Taxes &amp; Fees &#9654;</span>
        </div>
        <input type="range" id="mixSlider" min="0" max="100" value="50" step="1"
               aria-label="Choose the mix between service cuts and tax increases. 0 is all cuts, 100 is all new taxes and fees."
               aria-valuetext="50 percent cuts, 50 percent new taxes and fees">
        <div class="mix-readout" id="mixReadout" aria-live="polite"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="split">
        <div class="panel cuts">
          <h3>Closed by cutting services</h3>
          <div class="amount" id="cutAmt">$141.6M</div>
          <div class="sub" id="cutSub">Whole departments eliminated, smallest first</div>
          <ul class="conseq" id="cutList"></ul>
          <p class="note">Police, fire, and corrections are protected by the amendment, so cuts can only come from the roughly $247M of discretionary service departments. Departments are eliminated whole, smallest budget first. Because that pool is smaller than the $283.2M shortfall, even eliminating all of them leaves a remainder that taxes and fees must cover.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="panel taxes">
          <h3>Closed by raising taxes &amp; fees</h3>
          <div class="amount" id="taxAmt">$141.6M</div>
          <div class="sub" id="taxSub">Equivalent new revenue the City would need to find</div>
          <ul class="conseq" id="taxList"></ul>
          <p class="note">The City could legally raise property tax (its consolidated charter allows up to ~20 mills), but recovering the loss that way means a steep rate hike on a shrinking taxable base, which has little political support. So in practice the City would lean on sales surtax, service fees, and impact fees. These hit renters and lower-income households hardest.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="calc-foot">
        <b>How to read this.</b> The cut side spreads your chosen share of the $283.2M gap proportionally across all $901M of non-public-safety General Fund spending, using real FY2025-2026 figures. Most of that spending is non-departmental: debt service, pension contributions, transfers, and grants, much of which is legally or contractually fixed and hard to cut in practice. That is why a realistic cut would fall even harder on the visible service departments than the proportional split shown here. The tax side converts the same dollars into rough, illustrative equivalents: a one-cent local sales surtax raises on the order of $250-260M a year in Duval County, plus a flat fee spread across the City's roughly 390,000 parcels. These are scale estimates for public understanding, not precise rate forecasts; sales and property tax bases are not interchangeable.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

