<!-- SOURCES -->
<section id="sources" class="sources">
  <div class="inner">
    <div class="sec-num">Methodology</div>
    <h2>Sources and how the numbers were built</h2>
    <p>The $283.2 million figure comes from a parcel-level analysis of the Florida Department of Revenue's 2025 Name-Address-Legal file for Duval County (file NAL26F202501), covering all 398,317 parcels. The method applies an added $200,000 reduction to each homestead's non-school taxable value, floored at zero, then multiplies by the City's general services rate of 11.191 mills. Homestead general-services revenue falls from $409.3 million to $126.1 million, a loss of $283.2 million.</p>
    <p>Budget and staffing figures are drawn from the City of Jacksonville General Fund Operating Fund (00111) summary for FY2025-2026, including the $2,017,752,830 proposed General Fund, $1,191,159,774 in property tax revenue, and $731,948,235 in salaries. Department budgets and employee caps come from the same adopted budget document.</p>
    <p>The proposed exemption change reflects Florida Senate Joint Resolution 2-F (2026) and companion House measures HJR 201 through 213, which raise the homestead exemption in stages and restrict the use of remaining property tax revenue to public safety, education, infrastructure, and natural resources.</p>
    <p>The analysis estimates static revenue effects only. It does not model behavioral responses such as changes in housing prices or new construction, nor does it assume any state replacement funding. Tax-and-fee equivalents on the calculator are illustrative estimates of scale, not precise rate projections.</p>
